{{About|the technical mathematical concept of coincidence|numerical curiosities|mathematical coincidence}}
In [[mathematics]], a '''coincidence point''' (or simply '''coincidence''') of two [[function (mathematics)|mappings]] is a point in their common [[domain (mathematics)|domain]] having the same image.
Formally, given two mappings :<math>f,g \colon X \rightarrow Y</math> we say that a point ''x'' in ''X'' is a ''coincidence point'' of ''f'' and ''g'' if ''f''(''x'') = ''g''(''x'').<ref>{{citation | last1 = Granas | first1 = Andrzej | last2 = Dugundji | first2 = James | doi = 10.1007/978-0-387-21593-8 | isbn = 0-387-00173-5 | location = New York | mr = 1987179 | page = xvi+690 | publisher = [[Springer-Verlag]] | series = Springer Monographs in Mathematics | title = Fixed point theory | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4_iJAoLSq3cC&pg=PA531 | year = 2003}}.</ref>
Coincidence theory (the study of coincidence points) is, in most settings, a generalization of [[fixed point (mathematics)|fixed point]] theory, the study of points ''x'' with ''f''(''x'') = ''x''. Fixed point theory is the special case obtained from the above by letting ''X = Y'' and taking ''g'' to be the [[identity mapping]].
Just as fixed point theory has its [[fixed-point theorem]]s, there are [[theorem]]s that guarantee the existence of coincidence points for pairs of mappings. Notable among them, in the setting of [[manifold]]s, is the [[Lefschetz fixed-point theorem|Lefschetz coincidence theorem]], which is typically known only in its special case formulation for fixed points.<ref>{{citation | last = Górniewicz | first = Lech | contribution = On the Lefschetz coincidence theorem | doi = 10.1007/BFb0092179 | mr = 643002 | pages = 116–139 | publisher = Springer, Berlin-New York | series = Lecture Notes in Math. | title = Fixed point theory (Sherbrooke, Que., 1980) | volume = 886 | year = 1981}}.</ref>
Coincidence points, like fixed points, are today studied using many tools from [[mathematical analysis]] and [[topology]]. An [[Equaliser (mathematics)|equaliser]] is a generalization of the coincidence set.<ref>{{citation | last = Staecker | first = P. Christopher | arxiv = 1008.2154 | doi = 10.1016/j.topol.2011.05.032 | issue = 13 | journal = Topology and its Applications | mr = 2812471 | pages = 1615–1625 | title = Nielsen equalizer theory | volume = 158 | year = 2011}}.</ref>
