'''f(g) Scholar''' also known as '''fg Scholar''' was a graphing, spreadsheet, and calculator [[software]] package published by [[Future Graph, Inc.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=774110|title=Future Graph, Inc.: Private Company Information &ndash; BusinessWeek|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref><ref name="homepage">{{cite web|url=http://www.futuregraph.com/|title=Future Graph, Inc. Home Page|publisher=Future Graph, Inc.|accessdate=25 April 2017|archiveurl=http://matrix.skku.ac.kr/sglee/algebra/ct/khahn/graph/Future%20Graph,%20Inc_%20Home%20Page.htm|archivedate= April 11, 1997}}</ref><ref name="ServicesServices1997">{{cite book|last1=Services|first1=Corporate Technology Information|last2=Services|first2=OneSource Information|title=CorpTech directory of technology companies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3P1OAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=29 June 2010|year=1997|publisher=Corporate Technology Information Services, Inc.|isbn=978-1-57114-013-5}}</ref> The software received a number of awards as well as extensive press coverage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ldt.stanford.edu/~jvanides/math/Math%20Learning%20Issues%20v6-102.htm|title=f(g) Scholar|publisher=[[Stanford]]|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref> Although originally targeted towards technical academia in the fields of math, science, and engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.math.utk.edu/cgi-bin/k12_software.pl |title=Mathematics Archives &ndash; Other Software Sites |accessdate=29 June 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619024859/http://archives.math.utk.edu/cgi-bin/k12_software.pl |archivedate=19 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> primarily college students and teachers, the software did gain acceptance in the business world.<ref name="Inc.1993" /><ref name="comp base">{{cite web|url=http://torus.math.uiuc.edu/jms/m302/labs/o-progs.html|title=MATH 302: Topics in Geometry|last=Sullivan|first=John M|authorlink=John M. Sullivan (mathematician)|work=Computer Based Mathematics and Internet Resources|publisher=Department of Mathematics, [[University of Illinois]]|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terrificscience.org/freeresources/lessonpdfs/AspirinShelfLife.pdf |title=#02 The Aspirin Shelf-Life Scenario|last=F. Crabill,|first=Eugene|work=[[Internet Archive]]|accessdate=29 June 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060928103849/http://www.terrificscience.org/freeresources/lessonpdfs/AspirinShelfLife.pdf |archivedate = 28 September 2006}}</ref>

fg Scholar featured a calculator, its own programming language with macro support, the ability to import graphics, an automated formula builder, math templates, a spreadsheet with graphing capability, a full featured vector drawing module, and the ability to export files in a number of formats.<ref name="Inc.1993" />

==Features==
f(g) Scholar provided 12 types of charts including: bar, pie, area, three-dimensional area.<ref name="Inc.1993" />

f(g) Scholar supported the following graphic types: .WPG, .WMF, .CLP, .CGM, and .PIC.<ref name="Inc.1993">{{cite book|last=Inc.|first=InfoWorld Media Group,|title=InfoWorld|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-zoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA120|accessdate=28 June 2010|date=1993-10-18|publisher=InfoWorld Media Group, Inc.|page=120}}</ref>

